				\begin{document}$$\varOmega (\log n)$$\end{document}) up to which no advantage compared to constant time is possible. Meanwhile, Kim and McCloskey [13] and Sommerhalder and Westrhenen [21] analyze the constant-time case subject to different acceptance conditions and characterize it based on the locally testable languages, a subclass of the regular languages.

Indeed, as covered in Sect. 3, the defining property of the locally testable languages, that is, that words which locally appear to be the same are equivalent with respect to membership in the language at hand, effectively translates into an inherent property of acceptance by sublinear-time ACAs. In Sect. 4, we prove a time hierarchy theorem for sublinear-time ACAs as well as further relate the language classes they define to the regular languages and the parallel computation classes \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
